# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chinese-eight-ball-world-championship
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/2015-chinese-eight-ball-world-championship] The **2015 CBSA World Chinese Eight-ball Championship** (also known as the **2015 Chinese Pool World Championship**) was a professional pool tournament that took place from 24 January to 2 February 2015.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/2015-chinese-eight-ball-world-championship] The event was held in the First High School Stadium in Yushan, Jiangxi in China.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/2015-chinese-eight-ball-world-championship] This tournament was the inaugural CBSA World Chinese Eight-ball Championship event, played under the Chinese eight-ball rules.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/2015-chinese-eight-ball-world-championship] Darren Appleton won the event, defeating Mark Selby in the final 21–19.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/2015-chinese-eight-ball-world-championship] Chinese players Liu Haitao and Chu Bingjie were third and fourth respectively.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/2015-chinese-eight-ball-world-championship] The women's competition was won by Bai Ge who defeated Zhang Xiaotong 17–13.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/2015-chinese-eight-ball-world-championship] Yu Han came in third place, with Allison Fisher in fourth place.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships] The **Aerobic Gymnastics World Championships** are the World Championships for aerobic gymnastics.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] The UIM-ABP **Aquabike World Championship** is a powerboating sports competition.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] The UIM-ABP Aquabike World Championship is the premier class of jetski racing, founded in 1992.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Aquabike jetskis are personal watercraft vehicles purpose-built for racing and modified according to class.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] The UIM-ABP Aquabike World Championship is organized and promoted by H2O Racing Ltd on behalf of the Union Internationale Motonautique (UIM), the governing body of powerboating and the exclusive entity recognized by the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] This term refers to an Aquabike designed to be stood upon and is powered by rear jet propulsion with a completely closed system.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Skis, by definition, are the most demanding to ride as they require high fitness levels and great physical strength as well as agility in the legs and arms.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] According to the different degrees of modifications to the engine and bodywork, this type of Aquabike is used for three different categories: GP1, GP2 and Stock.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Another category (GP3) also exists in which younger drivers, between the ages of 11 and 14, compete.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Ski bikes are also used in the Freestyle category however this requires further structural changes to the size and motor, allowing the Ski to become considerably shorter in length, lighter in weight and able to perform better at low engine speeds.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Ski bikes are currently used in three different disciplines of the UIM-ABP Aquabike World Championship: Closed Circuit, Parallel Slalom and Freestyle.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Runabout refers to the largest and most powerful bikes in the Championship.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Runabout bikes are designed for driving while seated and feature a saddle (located towards the front) and a rear jet or a completely closed propulsion system.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Runabouts are the most common jetski in the world, as they can also be used for recreational purposes.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] As with Ski bikes, Runabout bikes are used for three different racing categories: GP1, GP2 and Stock, according to the different degrees of modifications to the engine and bodywork.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Runabout bikes are used in five different disciplines of the UIM-ABP Aquabike World Championship: Closed Circuit, Offshore, Endurance, Jet Raid and Parallel Slalom.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Regulations require that the path does not exceed 1300m in length.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] The circuit is marked out by different coloured buoys: yellow (right turn) and red (left turn).
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Riders are required to complete a set number of laps (varies according to racing division) at the end of which, the chequered flag is waved by marshals.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] These races are held across long distances and require serious consideration to be taken for refuelling as this is usually done on land.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] The circuit is bordered by large buoys (visible from long distances) or by natural landmarks like coastline, lighthouses, islands, rocks, etc .
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Endurance races are held on long closed circuits.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] As endurance races are testing the long-term resistance of a rider and their bike, these races tend to last several hours and are more akin to a marathon as opposed to a sprint.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Given the long duration of the race, supplies are required in advance to ensure everything runs smoothly.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Runabout bikes are used in endurance races.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] These races are spread over several stages.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Riders are required to travel long distances marked by checkpoints to complete the race.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] These races are often very time consuming as riders cover one expanse of water, and reach the coast on the other side, where their bike then has to be transported by land to the next race stage.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] This category is more of a competition than a race.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Riders are given a duration of three minutes to perform a rehearsed routine, one at a time.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] The stunts are evaluated by a team of five expert judges.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] The evaluation criteria are: quality, quantity and variety.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] The most common moves are Backflip, Barrel Roll, 360, Superman and Submarine.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Safety and security is of paramount importance during all the races and tests.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] Each member of the rescue team present at all races is required to have a certificate proving their ability to rescue and transport personal watercraft and injured riders.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] The support of the firefighters and patrol boats is essential as they ensure the immediate action in case of more serious accidents.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] On the ground, there is a medical team specialised in traumatology who are able to accompany the riders to the closest hospital to the race site.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/aquabike-world-championship] In offshore racing, there is also a helicopter rescue service.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/archery-world-cup] The **Archery World Cup** is a competition **outdoor**organized by World Archery, where the archers compete in four stages in four countries and the best eight archers of each category (from 2010, four archers during 2006–09) advance to an additional stage to contest the Archery World Cup Final.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/archery-world-cup] It has received plaudits for its innovative approach to the sport, raising its profile and reach.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/archery-world-cup] From 2013, the World Cup is broadcast live on Eurosport.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/archery-world-cup] It carries sponsorship from Kia and Longines, which supports the annual Longines Prize of Precision for archery, for the "best male and female athletes that master bow and arrow through concentration, balance, accuracy, and skill".
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/archery-world-cup] The following venues have hosted stages of the World Cup Final.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/archery-world-cup] The Longines Prize for Precision is awarded to the male and female archers who shoot the most 10s over the course of the competition at the end of the season.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/archery-world-cup] It has been awarded since 2010 and is awarded to compound and recurve archers in alternate years.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/archery-world-cup] Winners receive a trophy, watch and cash prize of 5,000 CHF.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/archery-world-cup] The following table shows the total number of all medals (including stage and finals).
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/archery-world-cup] The following table shows the total number of individual medals (including stage and finals).
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/archery-world-cup] An **Indoor Archery World Cup** was inaugurated in 2010.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/archery-world-cup] It is played in the off-season (November to February), with fewer stages and the final competed in Las Vegas.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/archery-world-cup] In 2014, the stages were held in Marrakesh, Singapore and Telford.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/archery-world-cup] 2019-2020 Indoor Archery World Series have 6 qualification and one final stage.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/archery-world-cup] After 2018, the World Indoor Archery Championships were discontinued, leaving the Indoor Archery World Series as the premier championship in indoor archery.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-billiards-world-championship] The **Artistic Billiards World Championship** is a carom billiards tournament in the discipline of artistic billiards, organized by the Confédération International de Billard Artistique.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-billiards-world-championship] Raymond Steylaerts of Belgium won the tournament six times, more than any other player.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-billiards-world-championship] The winners have mainly been European, and more commonly Belgian.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The **Artistic Gymnastics World Championships** are the world championships for artistic gymnastics governed by the Fédération Internationale de Gymnastique (FIG).
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The first edition of the championships was held in 1903, exclusively for male gymnasts.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Since the tenth edition of the tournament, in 1934, women's events are held together with men's events.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The FIG was founded in 1881 and was originally entitled FEG (Fédération Européenne de Gymnastique), but changed its name in 1921, becoming the Fédération Internationale de Gymnastique (FIG); this name change roughly correlates with the actual naming of the World Championships.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Although the first such games were held in 1903, they were not initially entitled the 'World Championships'.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The first competition ever actually referred to as a 'World Championships' at the time was a competition held in 1931 that, while referred to in an official FIG publication as the "First Artistic Men's World Championships", often seems to go ignored by various authorities in the sport.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The championships prior to the 1930s, beginning back in 1903, would eventually be recognized, retroactively, as the World Championships.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Additionally, repeat World All-Around Champion from 1909 and 1913, Marco Torres was also French-Algerian as he was born in Sidi Bel Abbès.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Perhaps the first African delegation was the Egyptian one which offered forth a full male team at the 1950 World Championships in Basel.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] By the time of these World Championships, a total of 60 male athletes from 6 countries and 53 female athletes from 7 countries comprised the competitive field.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] By the 2013 World Championships, the competition had grown to include 264 men from 71 countries and 134 women from 57 countries.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] As of 2023, over fifty editions of the championships have been staged, and over fifty countries have earned medals in artistic gymnastics events.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The most successful nation, both in gold medal results and total number of medals, is the former Soviet Union (not including medals from its successor states), and China is the second.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The United States is the third most successful country in gold medal results while Japan is the third in total number of medals.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Since the fall of the Iron Curtain, the traditional powerhouses in men's and women's individual still had expressive results: Russia, Belarus, Ukraine, China, United States, Japan, and Romania.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The last two decades were marked by increasing results from two emerging powers: Great Britain and Brazil and at the same period a big decrease in results from Belarus, Romania and Ukraine.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] However, this cycle was broken in 2021, when the COVID-19 pandemic led to the 2020 Summer Olympics to be delayed by one year, the edition scheduled for that year was not cancelled.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] While the Games were held between July and August 2021, the World Championships was allocated to the end of the same year.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] † The FIG (now World Gymnastics) in their 125-year anniversary publication, whereas pre-World War I editions of these championships are concerned, credits the teams and athletes from the Bohemian/Czech lands, then part of Austria-Hungary, as belonging to Czechoslovakia.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] †† There seems to be a history of inconsistency from the FIG's publications regarding whether these 1931 games are considered to be a World Championships.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Last updated after Day 7 of the 2025 World Championships.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Early events such as the 1913 and 1911 championships were purely team events without any individual awards, individual scores were only introduced in 1922, with the first all-round individual men's champion being recognised in that year.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Similarly the first women's championship in 1934 only had medals being awarded to teams, not individuals.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Individual "medals" for these events were therefore only recognised retrospectively and weren't awarded at the time.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Similarly, until 1921 FIG was known as the *European* Gymnastics Federation (*FEG*) and its events were not world championships as such.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] This brief biographical treatment was published at least as far back as 14 January 2017 on the official Facebook website of his alma mater in a photograph album, begun on 29 November 2016, containing other such brief biographical treatments of its notable alumni.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Boldface denotes active artistic gymnasts and highest medal count among all artistic gymnasts (including those not included in these tables) per type.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Few non-primary sources state that at the 1938 World Artistic Gymnastics Championships, in Prague, Vlasta Děkanová of Czechoslovakia won 2 or 3 golds on multiple apparatuses.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The only primary source on the subject, a book officially released by the International Gymnastics Federation containing the results of the World Championships from 1903 to 2005, informs that medals were distributed only in the team all-around event and in the individual all-around event.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Therefore, according to official reports, Děkanová's official number of gold medals is four, two in individual all-round (1934 and 1938) and two in team events (1934 and 1938) - not six or seven.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Only nations with medals in five or more events are listed.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Positions below third place are not taken into account.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Results for Germany and West Germany have been combined.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Only nations with medals in three or more events are listed.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Positions below eighth place are not taken into account.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-skating-world-championships-p01] The **Artistic Skating World Championships** ('Worlds') is an annual artistic roller skating competition sanctioned by World Skate (previously the International Roller Sports Federation; FIRS) in which elite figure skaters compete for the title of World Champion.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-skating-world-championships-p01] First held in 1946, the event is regarded the most prestigious of the sport and a world title is considered to be the highest competitive achievement in artistic skating.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-skating-world-championships-p01] Skaters compete in many different categories such as men's singles, ladies singles, pairs, and junior categories at the World Championships.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/artistic-skating-world-championships-p01] Due to the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, World Skate banned Russian and Belarusian athletes and officials from its competitions, and will not stage any events in Russia or Belarus in 2022.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/chinese-eight-ball-world-championship] The **World Chinese Eight-ball Championship** (now known as the **WPA World Heyball Championship**) is a pool tournament in the discipline of Chinese eight-ball.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/chinese-eight-ball-world-championship] The event has been held annually since 2015, first taking place in Yushan, Jiangxi in China.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/chinese-eight-ball-world-championship] The tournament is one of the highest-paid pool tournaments in the world.
[src:chinese-eight-ball-world-championship/chinese-eight-ball-world-championship] Below is a list of results from the tournament starting from its inception in 2015.
